* {{note|alif|1}} In the beginning of a word, <font size="4">آ</font> ([[Harakat#Madda|alif with madda]]) represents the long vowel {{IPA|/[[Open back unrounded vowel|ɑ]]/}} (eg. <font size="3">آس</font> - {{unicode|'''ā'''s}}, "horse"), and <font size="4">ا</font> (alif) represents the consonant {{IPA|/[[Glottal stop|ʔ]]/}} (eg. <font size="3">اسلام</font> - {{unicode|'''ʾ'''islām}} or {{unicode|islām}}, "Islam"). In the middle or end of a word, <font size="4">ا</font> represents the long vowel {{IPA|/ɑ/}} preceded by a consonant (eg. <font size="3">كال</font> - {{unicode|k'''ā'''l}}, "year"; and <font size="3">نيا</font> - {{unicode|ny'''ā'''}}, "grandmother").
* {{note|zs|2}} The pronunciations of <font size="4">ږ</font> and <font size="4">ښ</font> depend on the dialect - eg. Kandahar<ref>Michael M.T. Henderson, [http://www.scribd.com/doc/6541839/Four-Varieties-of-Pashto ''Four Varieties of Pashto'']</ref>: {{IPA|/[[Voiced retroflex fricative|ʐ]]/}} and {{IPA|/[[Voiceless retroflex fricative|ʂ]]/}}; Quetta: {{IPA|/[[Voiced postalveolar fricative|ʒ]]/}} and {{IPA|/[[Voiceless postalveolar fricative|ʃ]]/}}; southern Wazirwola: {{IPA|/[[Voiced alveolo-palatal fricative|ʑ]]/}} and {{IPA|/[[Voiceless alveolo-palatal fricative|ɕ]]/}}<ref>[http://www.khyber.org/publications/016-020/ormuri.shtml Rozi Khan Burki, ''Dying Languages; Special Focus on Ormuri'']</ref>; Wardak: {{IPA|/[[Voiced palatal fricative|ʝ]]/}} and {{IPA|/[[Voiceless palatal fricative|ç]]/}}; Yusufzai: {{IPA|/[[Voiced velar plosive|ɡ]]/}} and {{IPA|/[[Voiceless velar fricative|x]]/}}. 
* {{note|jc|3}} The pronunciation of the letter <font size="4">ځ</font> merges with {{IPA|/[[Voiced alveolar fricative|z]]/}} in northern and eastern dialects, and <font size="4">څ</font> merges with {{IPA|/[[voiceless alveolar fricative|s]]/}} in eastern dialects.
* {{note|rr|4}} The letter <font size="4">ړ</font> represents {{IPA|/[[Retroflex lateral flap|ɺ̡]]/}} if it is not at the final position of a [[syllable]]; if it is final, it represents {{IPA|/[[Retroflex approximant|ɻ]]/}}.
* {{note|f|5}} <font size="4">ف</font> tends to be pronounced as <font size="4">پ</font>.
* {{note|ə|6}} The letter <font size="4">ۀ</font> representing {{IPA|/[[Mid central vowel|ə]]/}} is not used in many texts; instead <font size="4">ه</font> is used which can also represent {{IPA|/ə/}}.
* {{note|j|7}} <font size="4">ى</font> represents {{IPA|/ai/}} if preceded by a consonant (eg. <font size="3">لرګى</font> - {{unicode|larg'''ai'''}}, "wood"), and represents {{IPA|/j/}} if preceded by a vowel (eg. <font size="3">دوى</font> - {{unicode|du'''y'''}}, "they").
* {{note|loan|8}} Ten of the alphabets, <font size="4">ق ف ع ظ ط ض ص ح ﺫ ث</font>, appear only in loanwords which are mostly of Arabic origin. Eight of them, <font size="4">ع ظ ط ض ص ح ﺫ ث</font>, represent no additional phonemes of Pashto, and their pronunciation merges with other phonemes.

In the earliest known Pashto manuscript written in 1651 CE,<ref>[http://www.khyber.org/publications/026-030/standardpashto.shtml D. N. MacKenzie, "A Standard Pashto",  Khyber.org]</ref> <font size="4">ڊ</font> (dāl with subscript dot) was used for {{IPA|/t͡s/}} and {{IPA|/d͡z/}}, which was still used in the Diwan of Mirza written in 1690 CE, but this sign was soon replaced by <font size="4">څ</font> which was first attested in 1696-7 CE. <font size="4">څ</font> is now used for only {{IPA|/t͡s/}}.

